This PR adds a new Blazor analyzer that detects when `ElementReference` instances are accessed outside of the `OnAfterRenderAsync` or `OnAfterRender` lifecycle methods, which can lead to runtime errors due to accessing stale or non-existent element references.

## Problem

Developers often try to access `ElementReference` fields or properties in other component lifecycle methods like `OnInitialized`, `OnParametersSet`, or in event handlers. This practice is problematic because:

- Element references are only valid after the component has been rendered
- Accessing them before rendering can result in null references or stale data
- This is a common source of confusion and runtime errors in Blazor applications

## Solution

The new `ElementReferenceUsageAnalyzer` (diagnostic ID: `BL0009`) analyzes component code and reports warnings when:

- `ElementReference` fields or properties are accessed outside of `OnAfterRenderAsync` or `OnAfterRender` methods
- This applies to both direct field access and property access
- The analyzer only runs on types that implement `IComponent` to avoid false positives

## Example

```csharp
public class MyComponent : ComponentBase
{
    private ElementReference myElement;

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        // This will now produce a warning: BL0009
        var elementId = myElement.Id;
    }

    protected override async Task OnAfterRenderAsync(bool firstRender)
    {
        // This is allowed - no warning
        if (firstRender)
        {
            await myElement.FocusAsync();
        }
    }
}
```

The analyzer provides clear guidance to developers about when and where `ElementReference` instances should be accessed, helping prevent common runtime issues in Blazor applications.

Fixes #63247.

