The `RedirectToLogin.razor` component in the Blazor WebAssembly project template was using a hardcoded authentication path, which is outdated since .NET 7+ breaking changes for WebAssembly authentication.

## Problem

The current implementation hardcodes the login path:

```razor
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.WebAssembly.Authentication
@inject NavigationManager Navigation

@code {
    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        Navigation.NavigateToLogin("authentication/login");
    }
}
```

This approach doesn't follow the recommended pattern for .NET 7+ and prevents proper configuration of authentication paths.

## Solution

Updated the component to use dependency injection and configuration options:

```razor
@inject NavigationManager Navigation
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.WebAssembly.Authentication
@using Microsoft.Extensions.Options

@inject IOptionsSnapshot<RemoteAuthenticationOptions<ApiAuthorizationProviderOptions>> Options
@code {
    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        Navigation.NavigateToLogin(Options.Value.AuthenticationPaths.LogInPath);
    }
}
```

This change:
- Uses `IOptionsSnapshot<RemoteAuthenticationOptions<ApiAuthorizationProviderOptions>>` to access configuration
- Replaces hardcoded path with `Options.Value.AuthenticationPaths.LogInPath`
- Maintains backward compatibility (default `LogInPath` is still "authentication/login")
- Follows the patterns established in the existing test suite
- Makes the component properly configurable for different authentication scenarios

Fixes #63199.

